# Deleting Data from the Database Using Hibernate:

    Imagine you are managing a list of students in a school database. One day, a student leaves the school, and you need to remove
    their details from the system. Instead of writing complicated SQL queries like DELETE FROM student WHERE id = ?,
    Hibernate makes this process much simpler.

    Hibernate allows you to delete records directly from your Java application by working with objects instead of database tables.
    In this guide, we will explore how to delete a student’s data step by step using Hibernate’s session.remove() method.

Q1. Why Learn Deleting Data in Hibernate?
    Deleting data is a routine operation in most applications:
        1. In a school database, you may need to remove records of students who have graduated.
        2. In an e-commerce app, you might delete discontinued products.
        3. In a library system, old book entries may be removed.
    Hibernate allows you to delete records using Java objects instead of manually writing SQL queries.
    This makes your code cleaner, more secure, and easier to maintain.

